TGA tests were conducted in air at a rate of 5 °C/min over a temperature range of 50 to 800 °C to estimate the weight percentage of water crystallization and graphene in the CVH composites (Fig. 3
                        b). The release of adsorbed crystalline water caused a weight loss of about 8.35 % for the pure VO2(D) material in the temperature range of 100–350 °C. One can calculate the amount of H2O to be about 0.2 % per unit based on the 8.35 % weight loss. Between 350 and 800 °C, there was a weight gain of roughly 6.1 %, which can be explained by the transformation of VO2 into V2O5. Regarding CVH, the TGA plots additionally demonstrate a sharp mass loss between 100 and 350 °C as a result of the water molecules being extracted from VO2 and graphene. In contrast to pure VO2, the CVH TGA plots exhibit a brief mass gain between 350 and 400 °C, which is explained by the VO2 material's conversion to V2O5. Following this, the composite loses 4.55 % of its weight as the temperature rises from 400 to 800 °C. This is caused by graphene's carbon skeleton burning. The 2.3 % weight gain of VO2 and the CVH's 4.55 % weight loss from 400 to 800 °C can be used to estimate the amount of graphene present in the CVH. The 2.3 % weight gain of VO2 and the CVH's 4.55 % weight loss from 400 to 800 °C can be used to estimate the amount of graphene present in the CVH. Assuming the complete conversion of VO2 to V2O5 in the comparison material, one can estimate the proportion of HG and CQD in the CVH composite to be about 10.65 % in total. See (Fig. 4
                        ).
